Today i am uploading a "TOILET PAPER PRINTER- HOLDER" for the bathroom.
There are a lot of cool Toilet paper holders on thingiverse, so i decided to add something i made.
Because the size of this print i divided it in half. after printing it you can put it all together.
The model consist of:

  2. Two parts of the spool, on which the toilet paper rolls on. one side has a bolt which you can unscrew and change the paper .
    3.bolt.
    4.Cylinder (print 3) , use them to connect the two halves of the printer. also connect the two halves of the bar and glue them .
    The Printer has a 2 mounting holes at the back for mounting.

Visit my instructable tutorial for more details, tips and complete instructions: http://www.instructables.com/id/DC-Through-Coil-Motor/

Short story behind this motor:
One day my brother sign himself for a thesis to develop new type of electric motor. Funny part is that he want to be a dentist and have no knowledge about electric stuff at all. Its quite challenge to do invention on something really old and proved like electric motor. But I was quite impressed about his ideas how inventive motor should work, i found some problems with the concept and after few talks we came up with this. We was not able to find similar type of motor on the market so we decided to make prototype. Please let me know in comments if this concept of motor is described somewhere.

Idea:
Difference from conventional motor is that rotor of our motor goes directly through coil. It works like rounded coil gun, if you take end of the coil gun and connect it back to start point. Advantage is that rotor magnet is crossing directly center of coil where is the highest magnetic force from the coil created. Conventional motors just pass around the coil, problem with them is that coil is then winded in really small length to have center of coil close to magnet. Small length of coil means more layers = more length of magnet wire = less efficiency. So we think that our motor should be more efficient. We start with two pole motor and then made this four pole one I am sharing there, four pole have many advantages. Please read my instructables where i will try to explain all details and our thinking.
This motor have also disadvantage with the construction and complexity to build, i see big advantage to combine this motor with planetary gear, or in applications without output gear like gyro stabilization. 3D print technology really help us to bring this to live.

Future improvements:
Two part wheels have to be glued together, redesign will improve functionality.
Optical gate to switch coils instead of mechanical switch.
Redesign wheel to output shafts, do planetary gear to one output shaft.
More poles.

description.text:
This is a reflector for any radio with a round antenna with stepped diameters in the shaft. The top hole is 8mm and the bottom hole is 9.5mm and you may have to clean these up to make it fit properly.

The basic premise is that it will reflect radio waves forward and theoretically boost the range. I looked at other range boosters and believe that the designs are wrong. The actual antenna is somewhat shorter than the overall length of the antenna and for a 2.4Ghz frequency, the actual antenna is about 31mm at the end of the shaft. This design allows the reflector to sit directly behind the actual antenna rather than below it.

I have not yet tested the range, but plan to do so today.

title: Spiral staircase display stand e.g. for chess sets

description.text:
I recently made a chess set (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1508763) and wanted to be able to display it without taking up too much shelf space.

I liked the stand by SteedMaker (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:580331) but it was too modern and organic for my more 'gothic-esque' chess set so I designed this spiral staircase stand.

It is modular for easy printing and can be modified to your preference of steps, colour, column style or cap stone...my favorite is the knights helmet using the optional column supports and 6 steps to display each main piece once.

If you have 6 steps it will balance, but suggest you use the optional support columns which attaches to the 'step with column support'; this gives extra stability especially for expensive/heavy chess pieces.

You don't have to use it to just display chess sets!

If you want to fix the steps in place insert some 1.75 pla into one of the small holes on top of the step. This will index with a small notch on the bottom of the step to lock in place. Without this locking piece the steps can spin for 'free style'.

Assembly is pretty intuitive.

Ive included the twist and lock mechanism as a Sketchup file so you can make your own mods.

For the flag pole I used 3mm pla.

You don't have to print all the files uploaded you can mix and match. To make the design in the main photo print:
5 x steps with column support
1 x step without column support (this is the first step)
6 x main column round
1 x main column base
All support columns
1 x fluted spacer
The knights helmet

title: Simple Spool Holder for Ultimachine 5lb Spools

description.text: I was using a bearing hub and a piece of threaded rod to hold a spool, but as my collection of PLA grew, it was too much weight for the threaded rod and starting to use up all my 608 bearings. The PLA Spools from Ultimachine are 1.5" in diameter. My local Home Depot sells 10' long sticks of conduit for $12 and they cut it for free. (I went with 3', 3', 4'). The conduit fits nicely in the spools and they spin fine. There is a bit of friction which isn't a bad thing IMO, so the spools don't unwind too much accidentally. I have some slat-wall brackets that seem to work well, keeping the spools at a distance from the wall without letting them fall off the wall. NOTE: The measurements of the conduit at Home Depot is listed by inner diameter. 1.5" Conduit is too big - 1.25" Conduit fits well

1 Go to Home Depot.
2 Pick up 10' Conduit (1.25" Inner Diameter) from the Electrical Dept.
3 Try not to hit anyone.
4 Ask someone in an orange apron to cut it for you (optional).
5 Pay and hook it up.

title: Rigidbot 2 part cooling fan duct Rev2

description.text:
This Rev2 version has a beefier fan mounting arm for those who had trouble with it snapping on the original.

This is a high efficiency fan duct upgrade for the stock part cooling fan on a Rigidbot 2. This fan duct attaches using all stock parts so no modifications or extra parts are required to install it on a Rigidbot 2 printer. For best results read the print settings carefully.

The clip on the fan snaps onto the front bearing mount easily but securely and is easy to remove if needed. The pictures show the orientation and sequence to attach the fan duct and install the stock fan. (Same steps as the original so using some of the same pictures)

The fan duct design directs a concentrated high flow moderate pressure stream of cool air across the tip of the nozzle parallel to the top surface of the part removing the heat quickly from the area. This results in a much more uniform cooling pattern and surface finish even across thin and small parts greatly reducing warping and curling. Bridging capabilities are enhanced and features on the far side of the nozzle are stabilized. It is a truly awesome sight to watch the printer effortlessly create bridge spans of at least 15 mm with no visible sag and horizontal overhangs of up to 5 mm that are flat by the third layer. I use this piece as a test piece. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1088310

The air stream passes below the heater block so as to not cause temperature fluctuations across the head. The duct will clear all parts of the printer and does not interfere with or touch the guide rods.

Since this is a precision fit part I highly recommend using calibrated filament. My filament calibration object of choice is found here as it calibrates for the average diameter of the filament being used and its thermal expansion and cooling properties: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037301

To avoid melting the end of the installed duct it is recommended that the heater be pushed in nearly flush with the front of the heater block.

The STL file is Cura scaled and oriented for printing.

Printer:

Rigidbot 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1 mm

Infill:

24%

Notes:

Instructions below are for using PLA. Modify as needed for your material of choice.

This part will need supports with an overhang angle between 60 and 45 and fairly dense in the range of 25 - 30%. I also recommend a brim of 7 - 10 lines to anchor it to the bed more securely especially for the fan bolt mount which is the only place the part itself touches the bed.

First layer is printed at 0.2mm and the rest are at 0.1mm. Use a 0.8 shell and 0.8 top and bottom thickness at these resolutions. Start with the bed at 60 C and turn it down to 45 on layer 4 (0.5mm high). The stock cooling fan comes on full at layer 5 and provide adequate cooling for the first print of this part. I used my first test prototype to cool my second and final print. You may want to print a second fan using the first one produced using the stock cooling duct.

As mentioned above use calibrated filament for best fit results.

Post print clean up

Remove the support material from the back of the duct and any strings inside the duct. you should not have any support material inside the duct itself.

description.text:

4 quarter basis ( to build rounded base )
16 panels ( walls )
4 middle frames and 4 top frames

and then you can mount them together - without using any glue - they just match :)

If you want you can increase the height just by printing another 8 panels and 4 middle frames.

Quick outgoing mail flag I made because our wall mounted mailbox leaves no option to alert the mail carrier of outgoing mail other than leaving it hanging out.
